    "reasoning": "Problem 1: We analyze the polynomial $ P $ with integer coefficients satisfying $ P(0) + P(90) = 2018 $. Define $ Q(x) = P(x) + P(90 - x) $, which has integer coefficients and $ Q(0) = 2018 $. The goal is to minimize $ |Q(20)| = |P(20) + P(70)| $. Since $ Q(x) $ is symmetric around $ x = 45 $, it can be written as $ Q(x) = 2R((x - 45)^2) $ where $ R $ has integer coefficients. Thus, $ Q(20) = 2R(625) $ and $ Q(0) = 2R(2025) = 2018 \\implies R(2025) = 1009 $. For integer polynomials, $ R(625) - R(2025) $ is divisible by $ 625 - 2025 = -1400 $, so $ R(625) = 1009 + 1400k $ for integer $ k $, giving $ Q(20) = 2018 + 2800k $. The minimal $ |Q(20)| $ occurs at $ k = -1 $, yielding $ Q(20) = -782 $. For the symmetric polynomial $ P(x) = (x - 45)^2 - 1016 $, $ P(70) = -391 $. Thus, $ m = P(70) + 162 = -391 + 162 = -229 $.\n\nProblem 2: Milan starts with 2020 red and 2021 green balls. Each operation either preserves the total count (same-color draws) or reduces it by 2 (different-color draws). To reach 1 ball, exactly $ (4041 - 1)/2 = 2020 $ different-color draws must occur. Each different-color draw flips the parity of green balls. Initial green count is odd (2021), and 2020 flips (even) preserve parity. Final count must be odd, so the last ball is green with probability 1. Thus, $ \\lfloor 2021 \\cdot 1 \\rfloor = 2021 $.",
